# Input:
1. Input a subject video and select the number of frames to load with frame\_load\_cap.
2. Select the output width and height of the video
3. You can choose to skip input frames to reduce rendering time by increasing every\_nth.
4. Choose a seed value

### Tips:
- If you already have a mask video of the subject, un-mute the Upload Subject Mask group and upload it. This will override the Segment Dancer group.

# Prompt:
- Input a batch positive prompt in the green text area and a negative prompt in the red text area.
- Batch Format example:

"0" :"4k, bright sunshine outdoor buddhist temple, stephen_strange (dark blue outfit, dark blue pants, dark brown boots), red shoulder pads",

"20": "4k, colorful flower field with swirls and multi-color petals, stephen_strange (dark blue outfit, dark blue pants, dark brown boots), red shoulder pads",

etc...

# Sampler
- Bypass the Sampler group when trying to finalize masks.
- Un-mute HiRes Fix Group for final render to increase image quality. Recommend muting when testing the workflow.

# Controlnet:
- If you already have depth and openpose videos generated, you can un-mute the "Override" groups below and provide them via video upload. Otherwise they will be dynamically generated.
- Composite video is the final composite of mask dilations including the input subject mask.

# IPAdapters

### White:
- Subject mask image, upload a reference image for the subject (dancer).
### Black:
- Background mask image, upload a reference image for the initial background.
### Red:
- Red dilation mask image, upload a reference image for the red dilation mask area.
### Green:
- Green dilation mask image, upload a reference image for the green dilation mask area.
### Blue:
- Blue dilation mask image, upload a reference image for the blue dilation mask area.

# AnimateDiff:
- You can change or bypass the motion lora, I use LiquidAF with weight 0.8 by default.
- Increase/decrease the Multival Dynamic float to increase/decrease the amount of motion in the output.

# Models:
- I recommend using an LCM model (I used ParadigmLCM v1.0) and adding the lora AnimateLCM_sd15_t2v_lora.safetensors with strength 0.18 (Optional).
- Set Loras in the Lora Stacker with associated weights.

# Output
- Change the output location of the video file by updating the custom_directory string.
- Videos are saved in .../output/[date]/[custom_directory]

# Dilate Masks:
- Set how quickly the subject mask should dilate (expand) per frame for each mask color using "dilate_per_frame", I default to 10. Lower values will result in a slower dilation.
- Set a delay to wait number of frames before starting the mask dilation. It is useful to stagger dilation times by having a different delay for each mask color.

### Tip:
- Change the shape to "square" for faster processing speed, use it to get the timing and mask speed down and then switch to "circle" for final renders.
- Hide the preview images for masks if the editor start lagging
- Circle can take a while to generate, potentially minutes per mask.
- You can override the generation of dilation masks by bypassing each color mask group and providing a video via upload in the "Override Dilation Mask" group, and setting the boolean to "true".
